baseline = Sequential()
baseline.add(Dense(1024, input_dim=784))
baseline.add(Activation('relu'))
baseline.add(Dense(1024))
baseline.add(Activation('relu'))
baseline.add(Dense(1024))
baseline.add(Activation('relu'))
baseline.add(Dense(1024))
baseline.add(Activation('relu'))
baseline.add(Dense(1024))
baseline.add(Activation('relu'))
baseline.add(Dense(10))
baseline.add(Activation('softmax'))

Plotting the images 10 x 10 subplot for the second last layer output. Argmax is taken and the top 10 probabilites for each digit is displayed.The reason certain digits are missing is because the second last layer extracts features for only specific digits and not all as in the earlier 10 x 10 plot, that's the reason we are getting plots with missing spaces. Also, the dimension was 1024 out of which we selected 10 random dimensions for the experiment, which also makes a difference.

    for j in range(10):
        if findex[i] ==[] or j > len(findex[i])-1: 
          continue
        axis[i,j].imshow(np.reshape(xtest_sam[findex[i][j]],(28,28)))

PCA and tSNE for the raw iamges

In [ ]:
pca_dim = PCA(n_components=2)
xtest_pca = pca_dim.fit_transform(xtest_flat)
principal_df = pd.DataFrame(data = xtest_pca, columns = ['PCA 1', 'PCA 2'])
In [ ]:
unames, id, count = np.unique(ytest_flat, return_inverse=True, return_counts=True)
sum_pca_0 = np.bincount(id, weights=xtest_pca[:, 0])
sum_pca_1= np.bincount(id, weights=xtest_pca[:, 1])
mean_pca_0 = sum_pca_0 /count
mean_pca_1 = sum_pca_1 /count

The raw images in PCA are little difficult to classify because there are some overlappings, but still you can see different clusters overall.

In [ ]:
plt.scatter(xtest_pca[:, 0], xtest_pca[:, 1], s= 5, c=ytest_flat, cmap='Spectral')
plt.scatter(mean_pca_0,mean_pca_1,c=unames,cmap='Spectral',marker ="s", edgecolor ="black", s = 70)
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (15,5)
plt.gca().set_aspect('equal', 'datalim')
plt.colorbar(boundaries=np.arange(11)-0.5).set_ticks(np.arange(10))
plt.title('Visualizing MNIST through PCA for raw sample', fontsize=12);
plt.xlabel('Principal Component 1')
plt.ylabel('Principal Component 2')
Out[ ]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Principal Component 2')
In [ ]:
tsne = TSNE(n_components=2, random_state=0)
xtest_tsne= tsne.fit_transform(xtest_flat)
In [ ]:
unames, id, count = np.unique(ytest_flat, return_inverse=True, return_counts=True)
sum_tsne_0 = np.bincount(id, weights=xtest_tsne[:, 0])
sum_tsne_1= np.bincount(id, weights=xtest_tsne[:, 1])
mean_tsne_0 = sum_tsne_0 /count
mean_tsne_1 = sum_tsne_1 /count

The raw images in tSNE are better to classify as compared the the PCA, the clusters are clearly seperable. There does exist some overlapping though.

In [ ]:

sum_pca_0 = np.bincount(id, weights=forthlayer_pca[:, 0])
sum_pca_1= np.bincount(id, weights=forthlayer_pca[:, 1])
mean_pca_0 = sum_pca_0/count
mean_pca_1 = sum_pca_1 /count

As compared to the previous 2 plots the cluster overlappting has reduced and there is seperability visible, although it is not completly seperable.

In [ ]:
(xtrain, ytrain), (xtest,ytest) = mnist.load_data()

In [ ]:
initializer = tf.keras.initializers.RandomNormal(mean=0, stddev=0.01)
model1 = tf.keras.models.Sequential([
          tf.keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=(28,28)),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(512,activation='sigmoid',kernel_initializer=initializer),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(512,activation='sigmoid'),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(512,activation='sigmoid'),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(512,activation='sigmoid'),

 ])

Part 3

Activation function: the logistic sigmoid function; initialization: Xavier initializer; no dropout

In [ ]:
initializer = tf.keras.initializers.GlorotNormal()
model_1 = tf.keras.models.Sequential([
          tf.keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=(28,28)),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='sigmoid',kernel_initializer=initializer),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='sigmoid'),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='sigmoid'),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='sigmoid'),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='sigmoid'),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(10,activation='softmax')                               
 ])

In [ ]:
initializer = tf.keras.initializers.GlorotNormal()
model_2 = tf.keras.models.Sequential([
          tf.keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=(28,28)),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='sigmoid',kernel_initializer=initializer),
          tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='sigmoid'),
          tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='sigmoid'),
          tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='sigmoid'),
          tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='sigmoid'),
          tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(10,activation='softmax')                   
 ])

As you can see from the plot for Logistic with and wtihout dropout, the test loss is less for dropout as compared to without dropout. Also, the train loss suffers more in droppout since it is subjected to different feed forwards at every epoch which makes the model more robust.

Activation function: ReLU; initialization: Kaiming He’s initializer; no dropout

In [ ]:
initializer = tf.keras.initializers.HeNormal()
model_3 = tf.keras.models.Sequential([
          tf.keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=(28,28)),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='relu',kernel_initializer=initializer),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='relu'),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='relu'),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='relu'),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='relu'),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(10,activation='softmax')                 
 ])
In [ ]:
optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.0001)
model_3.compile(optimizer=optimizer,loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',metrics=['accuracy'])
In [ ]:
hist_3 = model_3.fit(xtrain,ytrain,epochs=300,validation_data=(xtest, ytest))

In [ ]:
initializer = tf.keras.initializers.HeNormal()
model_4 = tf.keras.models.Sequential([
          tf.keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=(28,28)),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='relu',kernel_initializer=initializer),
          tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='relu'),
          tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='relu'),
          tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='relu'),
          tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(1024,activation='relu'),
          tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
          tf.keras.layers.Dense(10,activation='softmax')                 
 ])
In [ ]:
optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.0001)
model_4.compile(optimizer=optimizer,loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',metrics=['accuracy'])
In [ ]:
hist_4 = model_4.fit(xtrain,ytrain,epochs=300,validation_data=(xtest, ytest))

plt.plot(hist_3.history['loss'])
plt.plot(hist_3.history['val_loss'])
plt.plot(hist_4.history['loss'])
plt.plot(hist_4.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('1024X5 Relu')
plt.ylabel('cross entropy loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['No Dropout: Train Loss x 1000', 'No Dropout: Test Loss','Dropout: Train Loss x 1000', 'Dropout: Test Loss'], loc='upper right')
plt.show()
